Here is a concise example of automatically generating a table of contents in LATEX:

\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Section 1}
\subsection{Subsection 1}
\section{Section 2}
\subsection{Subsection 2}

\end{document}

The key points are:

- Include the \tableofcontents command where you want the table of contents to appear
- Use \section and \subsection commands to divide the document into sections and subsections
- LATEX automatically generates the table of contents from the sectioning commands

Here is concise Latex code to draw a chessboard from a FEN notation:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\chessboard[setfen=r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R]

\end{document}

The key points are:

- Include the chessboard package 
- Use the \chessboard command
- Set the fen option to the FEN notation string to render that chessboard position

This will draw the chessboard with the pieces placed as described by the FEN string. The chessboard package handles all the underlying Latex commands to generate the board and pieces.

